<DocPage eyebrow="DOCS / RUNTIME ADAPTERS" title="Godot addon and other engines" lead="The .NET libraries, the Godot GDScript addon, and the native DLL use the same Gua contract from different sides. This page separates what belongs in the game from what belongs in the test runner." description="The difference between Gua's .NET bindings and Godot GDScript addon, the gua_godot DLL, and a practical porting boundary for Unity." section="docs">
  <Callout title="Research baseline"><p>This page follows <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/e82c7da92790b30bb8d534e5061fd3b2ebe00730">link1345/gua main at e82c7da, verified 2026-07-14</a>. Later releases may add targets, DLL names, and target frameworks.</p></Callout>

  <h2>The distinction</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Location</th><th>Used by</th><th>Responsibility</th><th>Engine-specific</th></tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/bindings/dotnet/src"><code>bindings/dotnet/src</code></a></td><td>.NET applications and out-of-process tests</td><td>C ABI P/Invoke, locators, waits, assertions, Godot process hosting, and visual comparison</td><td>Mostly neutral; <code>Gua.Testing.Godot</code> is Godot-specific</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/examples/godot-gdscript/addons/gua"><code>examples/godot-gdscript/addons/gua</code></a></td><td>A running GDScript Godot game</td><td>Reflects the Godot Control tree into Gua and applies external requests to real controls</td><td>Specific to Godot 4.7, GDScript, and GDExtension</td></tr>
  </tbody></table></div>
  <p>The first directory is a family of libraries for controlling and testing Gua from .NET. The second is an in-game runtime adapter. In a GDScript integration, the game uses the addon while an external test can use <code>Gua.Testing</code> and <code>Gua.Testing.Godot</code> over WebSocket.</p>

  <h2>What is in <code>bindings/dotnet/src</code></h2>
  <div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>Project</th><th>Responsibility</th><th>Where it runs</th></tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/bindings/dotnet/src/Gua.Core"><code>Gua.Core</code></a></td><td><code>GuaContext</code>/<code>IGuaContext</code> over the <code>gua.dll</code> C ABI; the NuGet package carries the Windows x64 native library</td><td>Any compatible .NET process that owns a local context; it does not observe engine UI by itself</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/bindings/dotnet/src/Gua.Testing"><code>Gua.Testing</code></a></td><td>Locators, waits, assertions, diagnostics, and test sessions</td><td>Usually the external test project</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/bindings/dotnet/src/Gua.Testing.Godot"><code>Gua.Testing.Godot</code></a></td><td>Godot process lifecycle, WebSocket connection, screenshots, and process output</td><td>Godot-specific external tests</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/bindings/dotnet/src/Gua.Testing.Visual"><code>Gua.Testing.Visual</code></a></td><td>Screenshot comparison and semantic recording/replay</td><td>External tests; it does not collect an engine's UI</td></tr>
  </tbody></table></div>
  <Callout kind="warn" title="C# does not mean automatic engine support"><p><code>Gua.Core</code> knows the Gua ABI, not Unity or Godot UI types. Every engine still needs a runtime adapter that walks its UI hierarchy, emits Gua nodes, and applies requested actions through the host UI.</p></Callout>

  <h2>What is in the GDScript addon</h2>
  <div class="table-wrap"><table><thead><tr><th>File</th><th>Responsibility</th></tr></thead><tbody>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/examples/godot-gdscript/addons/gua/gua.gdextension"><code>gua.gdextension</code></a></td><td>Declares the GDExtension entry point and platform library. It currently lists Godot 4.7 Windows debug x86_64 only</td></tr>
    <tr><td><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/examples/godot-gdscript/addons/gua/gua_auto_adapter.gd"><code>gua_auto_adapter.gd</code></a></td><td>Collects the root <code>Control</code> tree, reflects state, dispatches actions, emits events, and captures screenshots</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>bin/gua_godot.windows.debug.x86_64.dll</code></td><td>The GDExtension that registers a native <code>GuaContext</code> class for GDScript</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>bin/gua_runtime.dll</code></td><td>The shared Gua core, request/event queues, diagnostics, and Inspector WebSocket bridge</td></tr>
    <tr><td><code>plugin.cfg</code> / <code>plugin.gd</code></td><td>A minimal EditorPlugin shell that gives the directory conventional Godot addon packaging</td></tr>
  </tbody></table></div>
  <div class="flow"><span>Godot Control tree</span><b>→</b><span>gua_auto_adapter.gd</span><b>→</b><span>GuaContext (GDExtension)</span><b>→</b><span>gua_runtime.dll</span><b>→</b><span>Inspector / MCP / Tests</span></div>

  <h2>What <code>gua_godot.windows.debug.x86_64.dll</code> does</h2>
  <p>This C++ GDExtension is built from <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/native/gua-godot"><code>native/gua-godot</code></a>. Its <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/native/gua-godot/src/register_types.cpp"><code>gua_godot_library_init</code></a> entry registers <code>GuaContext</code> with <code>ClassDB</code> during Godot's Scene initialization. <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/native/gua-godot/src/gua_context.cpp"><code>GuaContext::_bind_methods()</code></a> exposes frame, node, action, event, reset, screenshot, and Inspector bridge operations to GDScript.</p>
  <p>GDScript cannot turn the Gua C ABI and C++ runtime into a Godot class by itself. The auto adapter loads <code>gua.gdextension</code> and calls <code>ClassDB.instantiate("GuaContext")</code>. A missing, stale, or incompatible DLL means that the adapter cannot create its context.</p>
  <Callout kind="tip" title="Two native responsibilities"><p><code>gua_godot...</code> translates Godot/GDScript types. <code>gua_runtime.dll</code> owns the shared runtime. The former links to the latter, so Windows packages normally place both in <code>addons/gua/bin</code>.</p></Callout>
  <p><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/examples/godot-gdscript/addons/gua/gua.gdextension"><code>gua.gdextension</code></a> loads the extension from <code>res://addons/gua/bin</code>. <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/native/gua-godot/CMakeLists.txt"><code>native/gua-godot/CMakeLists.txt</code></a> writes the build there, and the release workflow includes all addon DLLs in its ZIP.</p>
  <CodeBlock title="Build the Windows debug GDExtension" lang="powershell" code={`cmake --preset windows-msvc-debug\ncmake --build --preset windows-msvc-debug --target gua-godot`} />
  <Callout kind="warn" title="The Godot C# path does not use this DLL"><p><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/examples/dotnet-godot"><code>examples/dotnet-godot</code></a> P/Invokes <code>gua_runtime.dll</code> directly from <code>GuaGodotRuntime.cs</code>. The <code>gua_godot...</code> DLL is required by the GDScript path, not every Godot integration.</p></Callout>

  <h2>Applying Gua to Unity and other C# engines</h2>
  <h3>Reusable</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>The <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/protocol">protocol and JSON schemas</a>, Semantic UI Tree, and action/request/event contract.</li>
    <li>The <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/native/gua-core"><code>native/gua-core</code></a> C ABI, rebuilt as a native plugin for each target.</li>
    <li>The <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/tree/main/native/gua-runtime"><code>native/gua-runtime</code></a> bridge design. Its current WebSocket bridge is Win32-oriented, so other targets need porting.</li>
    <li><code>Gua.Testing</code> locators, waits, and assertions in an out-of-process .NET 10 runner connected to a Unity bridge.</li>
    <li>The adapter-owned reflection algorithm in <code>gua_auto_adapter.gd</code> and <code>GuaGodotRuntime.cs</code>.</li>
  </ul>
  <h3>Not reusable as-is</h3>
  <ul>
    <li>The Godot GDExtension DLL, descriptor, GDScript, and <code>Control</code>/<code>ClassDB</code>/<code>Viewport</code> code.</li>
    <li>The Godot type traversal/signals in <code>GuaGodotRuntime.cs</code> and the process/scene behavior in <code>GodotSceneTestHost</code>.</li>
    <li>The current <code>Gua.Core</code>/<code>Gua.Testing</code> assemblies inside Unity. They target <code>net10.0</code>, while Unity 6's official <a href="https://docs.unity3d.com/ja/current/Manual/dotnet-profile-support.html">profile matrix</a> does not support .NET Core managed plugins.</li>
    <li>A Windows debug x86_64 native DLL on macOS, Linux, mobile, Web, Release, or IL2CPP. Each target needs a build and <a href="https://docs.unity3d.com/ja/current/Manual/plug-ins.html">Unity Plugin Import settings</a>.</li>
  </ul>

  <h3>Recommended Unity architecture</h3>
  <div class="flow"><span>UI Toolkit / uGUI</span><b>→</b><span>UnityGuaAdapter.cs</span><b>→</b><span>native Gua plugin</span><b>→</b><span>WebSocket</span><b>→</b><span>.NET 10 test runner</span></div>
  <ol class="steps">
    <li><strong>Start with Windows x64 and one UI system.</strong><br />For UI Toolkit, walk the Visual Tree below <code>UIDocument.rootVisualElement</code>. For uGUI, start with <code>Selectable</code> objects below a Canvas. Unity's <a href="https://docs.unity3d.com/ja/current/Manual/UIE-UQuery.html">UQuery</a> can find UI Toolkit elements by name, USS class, and concrete type.</li>
    <li><strong>Write the native boundary as Unity-compatible C# source.</strong><br />Do not reference the existing <code>net10.0</code> assembly. Provide a thin C ABI P/Invoke/context wrapper using Unity's supported API profile.</li>
    <li><strong>Implement adapter-owned reflection.</strong><br />Begin a frame from <code>MonoBehaviour.Update</code> or an equivalent lifecycle hook; register id, role, text, bounds, visibility, enabled state, and value; then dispatch requests through the real Button, Toggle, input, selection, and scrolling paths and emit results.</li>
    <li><strong>Adapt bridge and screenshot behavior.</strong><br />Start the shared bridge and fulfill screenshot requests after Unity rendering. Godot's <code>Viewport</code> implementation is not portable.</li>
    <li><strong>Build a separate external host.</strong><br />Create a <code>UnityPlayerTestHost</code>-style launcher for Player lifecycle, ports, logs, and artifacts instead of copying <code>GodotSceneTestHost</code>. <a href="https://docs.unity3d.com/ja/current/Manual/com.unity.test-framework.html">Unity Test Framework</a> can complement this with Play Mode tests inside Unity.</li>
  </ol>
  <Callout kind="tip" title="Recommended reading order"><p><a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/protocol/specs/protocol.md">protocol.md</a> → <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/native/gua-runtime/include/gua/runtime.h">runtime.h</a> → <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/examples/godot-gdscript/addons/gua/gua_auto_adapter.gd">gua_auto_adapter.gd</a> → <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/examples/dotnet-godot/addons/gua/GuaGodotRuntime.cs">GuaGodotRuntime.cs</a> → <a href="https://github.com/link1345/gua/blob/main/bindings/dotnet/src/Gua.Testing.Godot/GuaRemoteContext.cs">GuaRemoteContext.cs</a>. This order separates protocol, native boundary, UI reflection, C# implementation, and external transport.</p></Callout>
</DocPage>
